1. CloudWatch Scenario (CPU spike 90%)
Check Amazon CloudWatch metrics (CPUUtilization graph)
Verify if spike is temporary or continuous
Check CloudWatch Alarms (configured or not)
SSH into EC2 → check processes (top, htop)
Check application logs (high traffic / memory leak / cron job)
Scale using Auto Scaling Group (add instances)
If needed → optimize app / restart service

# verify CloudWatch metrics and logs, 
then identify the process causing spike, and scale using ASG if required.

2. Jenkins Deployment Failure
Check Jenkins console output logs
Identify stage where failure happened (build/test/deploy)
Verify:
Git access / credentials
Build errors (dependency issue)
Server connectivity (SSH / permissions)
Re-run failed stage (if pipeline supports)

# Check disk space / environment variables
Fix issue → trigger pipeline again

3. S3 Access Issue
Check Amazon S3 bucket policy
Verify IAM role / user permissions
Check if object is public or private
Confirm Block Public Access settings
Validate correct URL / endpoint
If using CloudFront → check permissions there

4. High Availability Architecture
Deploy EC2 in multiple Availability Zones
Use Application Load Balancer (ALB)
Configure Auto Scaling Group
Store data in RDS Multi-AZ
Use Route 53 health checks
Static content → S3 + CloudFront

